[2]
Date: Tue 27 Feb 2017 12:01 PM EST
Source: WFLA [edited]
http://wfla.com/2018/02/27/legionnaires-disease-outbreak-reported-in-north-port-neighborhood/


The Sarasota County Health Department is investigating an outbreak of legionnaires' disease at the IslandWalk at the West Villages community in North Port (Florida). The Department of Health advised community officials to shut down the pool and spa on [Fri 23 Feb 2018].

Residents say at least 11 people were taken to area hospitals for treatment.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[North Port is a city with a population of 57 357 residents in 2010 in southern Sarasota County, Florida, United States. Located just north of the town of Port Charlotte (in Charlotte County, Florida), North Port is part of the North Port-Bradenton-Sarasota Metropolitan Statistical Area (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Port,_Florida). A map of North Port can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/North+Port,+FL.

IslandWalk at the West Villages is a gated community of single-family homes with a clubhouse and pool/spa (http://www.islandwalkvillage.com).

In addition to the community's pool/spa, the 1st news report above mentions that the community's landscape irrigation system is also suspected to be a potential source for the outbreak of legionnaires' disease in North Port, since landscape irrigation systems can generate aerosols during its operation. Inhalation of legionella in the form of an aerosol is a common mode of acquiring legionnaires' disease. Landscape irrigation systems can draw water from untreated lakes or reclaimed water in Florida (http://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/ae449 and http://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/ae448). Reclaimed or recycled water is wastewater from a sewer system that has been treated by a wastewater treatment plant to a level consistent with its intended use (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reclaimed_water).

Although legionellosis outbreaks have not been reportedly associated with use of reclaimed water, _Legionella_ species are commonly found in reclaimed water (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4584268/pdf/pathogens-04-00470.pdf).

Genotyping of clinical isolates, if available, will help establish a common source outbreak, if the genotypes match. However, if the diagnosis of legionnaires' disease was based only on a positive urinary antigen assay, there will be no isolates for genotyping. Matching the genotypes of clinical isolates with the genotypes of environmental isolates will help establish transmission pathways. - Mod.ML

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of North Port, Florida, United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5659038,32185.]
